The photocatalysis O2 reduction reaction (ORR) tests were also carried out in an outer irradiation-type photoreactor (Pyrex glass) connected to a closed gas-circulation system. High-purity O2 (99.9999%) was cycled by a gas-recycle-pump with tunable flow rates. Typically, 20 mg of the photocatalyst powders were dispersed in a mixture of water (40 mL) and isopropanol (10 mL). The dispersion was transferred into the catalysis system, thoroughly degassed to remove the air by high-purity Ar (99.9999%) displacement. After 30 min of high-purity (99.9999%) O2 bubbling, the dispersion was illuminated by a 300 W Xe-lamp (Beijing China Education Au-light Co., Ltd.) with a 420 nm long-pass filter. During the photocatalytic tests, the O2 was continuously bubbled at the flow rate of 120 mL min–1 into the dispersion, which was magnetically stirred at 800 rpm. The H2O2 decomposition reactions were carried out in a Pyrex glass vial. Twenty milligram of the catalyst powders were dispersed in a mixture of hydrogen peroxide (50 µmol), water (40 mL) and isopropanol (10 mL). The dispersion was transferred into the catalysis system, thoroughly degassed to remove the air by high-purity Ar (99.9999%) displacement. After that, the catalysis reactions were carried out under visible light irradiation. During the tests, the Ar was continuously bubbled at the flow rate of 30 mL min–1 into the dispersion, which was magnetically stirred at 800 rpm. The H2O2 concentration was measured by a cerium sulfate Ce(SO4)2 titration method based on the mechanism, that the yellow solution of Ce4+ could be reduced to colorless Ce3+ by H2O2 according to the following equation:12Ce4++H2O2→2Ce3++O2+2H+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
